SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 559
By Powers
A RESOLUTION to urge the United States Congress to pass the
Eliminating Discrimination And Creating
Corridors to Expand Student Success (ED
ACCESS) Act of 2022.
WHEREAS, the American Opportunity Tax Credit (AOTC) is the primary tax credit
available to students seeking higher education; and
WHEREAS, students with a felony drug conviction are permanently ineligible for this tax
credit; and
WHEREAS, the RAND Corporation has found that incarcerated individuals who
participated in correctional education programs had a forty-three percent lower chance of
recidivating than those who did not; and
WHEREAS, one such correctional education program in Tennessee administered by the
Tennessee Higher Education Initiative has a recidivism rate of less than one percent; and
WHEREAS, denying the AOTC to students with felony drug convictions makes it even
harder for this population to afford college and get their life on track; and
WHEREAS, making college less affordable for people convicted of drug felonies is not
an effective deterrent for drug crime, and no such restriction exists for other types of felonies,
such as murder; and
WHEREAS, former Congresswoman Diane Black (R-TN), also a former member of the
House of Representatives and Senate of the State of Tennessee, proposed the Student and
Family Tax Simplification Act, which passed the House in the 113th Congress and would have
repealed the AOTC's felony drug ban; and
WHEREAS, current members of the U.S. Congress have made recent attempts to
repeal the denial of the AOTC for students convicted of a felony drug offense, for example the
SJR0559
010576
- 1 -

Eliminating Discrimination And Creating Corridors to Expand Student Success (ED ACCESS)
Act of 2022, cosponsored by Senator Rob Portman (R-OH), Representative David Schweikert
(R-AZ), and Brad R. Wenstrup (R-OH); now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we urge the United States Congress to pass the
Eliminating Discrimination And Creating Corridors to Expand Student Success (ED ACCESS)
Act of 2022 or any similar legislation that eliminates the denial of the American Opportunity Tax
Credit for students convicted of a felony drug offense.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that a certified copy of this resolution be transmitted to
the Speaker and the Clerk of the United States House of Representatives, the President and the
Secretary of the United States Senate, each member of the Tennessee Congressional
delegation, the Attorney General of the United States of America, and the Attorney General of
the State of Tennessee.
